Halm says the same, and he refers to ‘ sacra majorum,' 0. 8. But this is not the correct interpretation. Cicero is speaking after Roman fashion 5 for, among the Romans, the ‘sacra,’ or sacred riteS, which a family had to perform, were a part of the ‘ hereditas ' or succession. It 1s no objection that this might not be a rule of Sicilian law ; Cicero speaks of it as if it were : “ In the Roman religious system there was a kind of divine worship, which was required from mere private persons, as a duty, and like every other, was under the superintendcnce of the Pontifices: ‘ sacra privata? If, for instance, a Roman

vowed certain offerings, and the Pontifices approved of them, he was for ever bound to this duty. Nay, this duty did not cease with his life, but, so far as was pos- sible, it must have perpetual continuance. For this reason the Pontifices assumed, that the obligation did not rest so much on the person as on the property, and passed with this property after the death to other persons '³ (Savigny, Vermischte Schriften, i. p. 152, ‘Ueber die Juristische Behand- lung der Sacra Privata bei den Riimern ³).
